[1]
Date: Thu 19 Sep 2002
From: Todd E. Cornish <TCornish@uwyo.edu>

A Response to the Query about the Accuracy of Diagnosis of West Nile Virus
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
I cannot comment on the cases seen at the Nebraska lab [see: West Nile
Virus, caprine & ovine - USA (NE) (03) 20020919.5356], but the "proof" in
Wyoming is the following on one of the clinically affected mountain goats:
Positive virus isolation from the brain.
Positive TaqMan RT-PCR from the brain.
Positive immunohistochemistry on the brain.
Appropriate microscopic lesions in the brain.
As an aside, there is no IgM capture ELISA test commonly available for
mountain goats or sheep -- these tests are species specific, and for mammals
(of the non-human variety) the only readily available test at most labs is
for equines.
--
Todd Cornish
Assistant Professor/Veterinary Pathologist
Wyoming State Veterinary Laboratory
<TCornish@uwyo.edu>

