[3]
Date: Fri 20 Sep 2002
From: Del Wilmot <delwindw@agr.state.ne.us>

Further Clarification on West Nile Virus in Mountain Goats and Sheep
--------------------------------------------------------------------
On 13 Sep 2002 the following information was posted. The Lincoln Veterinary
Diagnostic Laboratory of the University of Nebraska announced today that
samples from a mountain goat and a sheep have been shown to be positive for
West Nile Virus (WNV). Samples from both animals were positive on the
Reverse Transcriptase Polymerase Chain Reaction (RT-PCR) for WNV. The
samples were also positive by immunohistochemistry for WNV. The PCR results
were confirmed at the National Veterinary Services Laboratory (NVSL) and
virus isolation results are pending at NVSL.
The National Veterinary Service Laboratory (NVSL) has now confirmed that
West Nile Virus was isolated from both the sheep and mountain goat samples
by virus isolation(VI).
Summary: The NVSL has confirmed West Nile virus in samples from a sheep and
a mountain goat by: (1) Reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction
(RT-PCR), (2) Indirect immunofluorescence assay using a monoclonal antibody
specific for WNV, and (3) Virus Isolation.
--
Del Wilmot DVM
Deputy State Veterinarian
Nebraska Department of Agriculture
Bureau of Animal Industry
Lincoln, Nebraska
[ProMED-mail thanks these contributors for rapid clarification of the basis
for the diagnosis of West Nile virus infection in sheep and goats. - Mod.CP]
